46
00:05:46,100 --> 00:05:47,900
before the end-of-the-day's
package sort.

47
00:05:48,100 --> 00:05:52,200
<i>- That's how long we have.
That's how much time we have...
- [Translating]</i>

48
00:05:52,500 --> 00:05:55,300
Before this pulsating, accursed,
relentless taskmaster...

49
00:05:55,500 --> 00:05:58,000
tries to put us
out of business.

50
00:05:58,200 --> 00:06:01,100
Hey, Nicolai. Hey.
Nicolai, good to see you.

51
00:06:01,400 --> 00:06:03,200
How are you, kid?
Look what you did.

52
00:06:03,300 --> 00:06:05,300
You just delivered
your very first FedEx package.

53
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:08,900
That deserves something special,
like a Snickers bar...

54
00:06:09,200 --> 00:06:12,000
and a C.D. Player.

55
00:06:12,200 --> 00:06:14,000
And something to listen to...
a C.D. There.

56
00:06:14,200 --> 00:06:16,800
Elvis Presley.
Fifty million fans can't be wrong.

57
00:06:17,100 --> 00:06:18,900
You all recognize this,
don't you?

58
00:06:19,100 --> 00:06:21,600
I took the liberty
of sending this to myself.

59
00:06:21,900 --> 00:06:26,600
I FedEx'd it
before I left Memphis.

60
00:06:26,900 --> 00:06:28,900
You're probably wondering
what could be in here.

61
00:06:29,100 --> 00:06:31,300
What could it possibly be?
Is it architectural plans?

62
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:33,300
Maybe technical drawings?

63
00:06:33,500 --> 00:06:36,200
Is this the new wallpaper
for the... for the bathroom?

64
00:06:36,400 --> 00:06:38,200
<i>[Translator Continues]</i>

65
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:41,000
It is... a clock,

66
00:06:41,200 --> 00:06:43,000
which I started
at absolute zero...

67
00:06:43,200 --> 00:06:47,900
and is now at 87 hours,
22 minutes and 17 seconds.

68
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:52,900
From Memphis, America
to Nicolai in Russia, 87 hours.

69
00:06:53,200 --> 00:06:56,300
Eighty-seven hours
is a shameful outrage.

70
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:59,400
This is just an egg timer!

71
00:06:59,600 --> 00:07:02,200
What if it had been something else?
Like your paycheck?

72
00:07:02,500 --> 00:07:05,500
<i>- Or fresh boysenberries?
Or adoption papers?
- [Translating]</i>

73
00:07:05,700 --> 00:07:07,600
Eighty-seven hours
is an eternity.

74
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:09,700
The cosmos was created
in less time!

75
00:07:09,900 --> 00:07:12,500
Wars have been fought and
nations toppled in 87 hours!

76
00:07:12,700 --> 00:07:14,600
Fortunes made and squandered.

77
00:07:14,800 --> 00:07:16,700
[Translating]

78
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:20,600
<i>What?</i>

79
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:22,700
What are you saying
about me?

80
00:07:22,900 --> 00:07:24,700
I tell them,
what do they expect?

81
00:07:24,900 --> 00:07:28,400
This man, when his truck broke down,
he stole a boy's bicycle
to do his delivery.

82
00:07:28,700 --> 00:07:31,200
I borrowed it!
I borrowed a kid's bike.

83
00:07:31,400 --> 00:07:34,400
And I got my packages delivered,
and that is what you people
are gonna have to start doing.

84
00:07:34,700 --> 00:07:38,100
You have to start doing
whatever it takes, because
in three hours and two minutes...

85
00:07:38,300 --> 00:07:41,200
every one of these packages
has to be on the big truck...

86
00:07:41,600 --> 00:07:43,400
and on its way
to the airport.

87
00:07:43,500 --> 00:07:45,900
<i>- [Bell Rings]
- Fifteen minutes!</i>

88
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:49,300
- Crunch time! Crunch time!
- Crunch time!

89
00:07:49,500 --> 00:07:52,600
Let's go! Every package
on the airport truck.

90
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:54,800
Go!
Crunch, crunch, crunch!

91
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:56,800
- We have a big problem.
- What?

92
00:07:57,000 --> 00:07:59,600
- The truck in Red Square is stuck.
- What do you mean?

93
00:07:59,800 --> 00:08:02,300
- It's stuck.
- Stuck how? In snow? In ice?

94
00:08:02,500 --> 00:08:05,800
It's stuck! The most important truck...
the Kremlin truck! Many packages.

95
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:18,300
All right, all right, all right.
Let's put the table right here.

96
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:20,300
We'll just do the sort.

97
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:23,500
Ah, yeah, a clamp.
That would make us stuck.

98
00:08:23,700 --> 00:08:26,200
Let's go. Unload...
Get him out of there.

99
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:28,800
Right here.
Two lines, two lines.

100
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,700
One to the airport truck,
one to the Moscow truck.

101
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:33,500
Got it?

102
00:08:33,700 --> 00:08:37,100
C.D.G., F.E., M. E,
Memphis on the airport truck.
Everything else right there.

103
00:08:37,300 --> 00:08:39,900
Nicolai! Tick-tock, tick-tock.
Four minutes.

104
00:08:40,200 --> 00:08:42,200
[Ringing]

105
00:08:42,400 --> 00:08:44,900
[Answering Machine] Hi, this is Kelly.
If you're calling for Chuck, press one.

106
00:08:45,100 --> 00:08:47,200
Otherwise leave a message
after the tone. Thanks.

107
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:49,300
- [Beeps]
- [Chuck]
Hello, Kelly. Are you there?

108
00:08:49,400 --> 00:08:51,700
Pick up, pick up, pick up,
pick up. You're not there.

109
00:08:51,900 --> 00:08:54,800
<i>You're not gonna believe this. I'm doin'
the sorts in the middle of Red Square...</i>

110
00:08:55,100 --> 00:08:56,900
<i>in the shadow
of Lenin's tomb.</i>

111
00:08:57,100 --> 00:08:58,900
<i>#I miss you #</i>

112
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:01,000
# I miss you
I really wanna kiss you #

113
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:03,900
I'm outta here in two minutes and
I'm pickin' up the sweep through Paris,

114
00:09:04,100 --> 00:09:06,500
so I should be back in Memphis
about 18 hours or so.

115
00:09:06,900 --> 00:09:08,900
That's the good news.
The bad news is...

116
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:10,800
I gotta go to
the dentist this week.

117
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:12,800
I got something in there
that's hurtin'.

118
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:15,700
I love you and I'm gonna see you soon,
and you know what that means.

119
00:09:15,900 --> 00:09:18,400
Bye-bye. Nicolai! Tick-tock,
tick-tock, tick-tock, tick-tock!

120
00:09:24,500 --> 00:09:27,900
[Speaking French]

121
00:09:36,300 --> 00:09:40,000
- [Knocking]
- I absolutely, positively
have to get to Memphis tonight.

122
00:09:40,200 --> 00:09:42,100
Can't help you.
Try U.P.S.

123
00:09:42,400 --> 00:09:44,900
With this extra head wind, are we gonna
be able to push it and make the sort?

124
00:09:45,100 --> 00:09:47,300
- We'll do our best.
- "Our best," huh?

125
00:09:47,500 --> 00:09:51,600
Gwen, is there something wrong
with our doctors thatJack
keeps getting certified to fly?

126
00:09:51,900 --> 00:09:54,100
- Aren't you concerned?
- I'm terrified.

127
00:09:54,300 --> 00:09:56,200
But a girl's gotta do
what a girl's gotta do.

128
00:09:56,400 --> 00:09:59,100
That's the spirit.
Relentless is our goal. Relentless!

129
00:09:59,300 --> 00:10:02,300
What do you expect from the guy
who stole a crippled kid's bicycle...

130
00:10:02,500 --> 00:10:04,700
- when his truck broke down?
- I borrowed it.

131
00:10:04,900 --> 00:10:07,000
But I love that
the kid's now crippled.

132
00:10:07,200 --> 00:10:09,500
So you missed the last truck
by two minutes?

133
00:10:09,800 --> 00:10:12,500
Two minutes.
Actually, it was less than that.

134
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:15,600
The plane wasn't that heavy.
You could've added some fuel,

135
00:10:15,800 --> 00:10:17,600
picked up the speed
and made up the time.

136
00:10:17,800 --> 00:10:20,800
It's about the trucks.
Today's truck was two minutes late.

137
00:10:21,000 --> 00:10:23,900
Tomorrow's will be four minutes late,
and then six minutes
and eight minutes late.

138
00:10:24,100 --> 00:10:27,900
- Next thing you know,
we're the U.S. Mail.
- Yeah, well...

139
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:30,600
All I'm sayin' is, if you'd
gotten all those trucks on the plane,

140
00:10:30,800 --> 00:10:33,400
those Russkies would be
walking on water right now.

141
00:10:33,600 --> 00:10:35,900
Hey, don't...
Don't gimme that look.

142
00:10:36,100 --> 00:10:38,500
- It's just grape juice. Right, Chuck?
- Yeah.

143
00:10:38,700 --> 00:10:41,600
It's like a 1992
full-bodied grape juice.

144
00:10:41,800 --> 00:10:43,900
I see no evil, hear no evil,
speak no evil.

145
00:10:44,200 --> 00:10:47,400
We'd offer you some but, you know,
somebody's got to fly the plane.

146
00:10:47,700 --> 00:10:50,900
Yeah, well,
I "just say no," right?

147
00:10:51,100 --> 00:10:53,800
Listen, Stan,
I've been meaning to ask you.

148
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:55,900
How's Mary?

149
00:10:56,100 --> 00:10:59,300
Oh. Uh, well,

150
00:10:59,600 --> 00:11:02,500
- we really don't know anything yet.
- Mm-hmm.

151
00:11:02,700 --> 00:11:07,400
Uh, she went to
the doctor yesterday, and, uh,

152
00:11:07,700 --> 00:11:11,300
it hasn't meta...
metastasized...

153
00:11:11,600 --> 00:11:14,400
as far as they
can tell right now.

154
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:17,400
It's just kind of
wait and see.

155
00:11:17,600 --> 00:11:19,700
I'm so sorry.

156
00:11:19,900 --> 00:11:23,000
Tell her I'm gonna come by
and see her on my next layover.

157
00:11:23,200 --> 00:11:26,300
I want you to know, Stan,
we are all thinking about her and you.

158
00:11:26,600 --> 00:11:29,200
<i>- And just blessings.
- Thank you, Gwen.</i>

159
00:11:29,400 --> 00:11:31,800
<i>[Answering Machine] Hi, this is Kelly.
If you're calling for Chuck, press one.</i>

160
00:11:32,100 --> 00:11:34,800
Otherwise, leave a message
after the tone. Thanks.

161
00:11:40,200 --> 00:11:42,800
Stan.

162
00:11:43,100 --> 00:11:45,400
Listen.
Uh, I heard about this...

163
00:11:47,200 --> 00:11:50,300
I heard about this doctor
down in Emory, in Atlanta.

164
00:11:50,600 --> 00:11:52,400
Uh, he's supposed to be
the absolute best.

165
00:11:52,500 --> 00:11:54,500
He worked on
Frank Toretta's wife.

166
00:11:54,700 --> 00:11:56,500
Frank Toretta is
a systems analyst.

167
00:11:56,700 --> 00:11:59,000
He played center field for us.
You know him.

168
00:11:59,200 --> 00:12:01,800
In the softball tournament
last Labor Day.

169
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:03,700
Anyway, beside the point.

170
00:12:03,900 --> 00:12:08,300
Uh, what I was thinking is,
is that I could get his number...

171
00:12:08,600 --> 00:12:11,100
the doctor...
and, uh,

172
00:12:11,300 --> 00:12:13,600
you know,
put you all together and...

173
00:12:15,300 --> 00:12:17,600
You know, you could
get this thing fixed.

174
00:12:17,800 --> 00:12:19,600
You could beat it.

175
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:22,900
Thanks, Chuck.
[Sighs]

176
00:12:23,100 --> 00:12:25,500
So, I'll get his number.

177
00:12:25,700 --> 00:12:27,800
<i>[Elevator Bell Dings]</i>

178
00:12:38,400 --> 00:12:40,300
[Knocking]

179
00:12:47,900 --> 00:12:51,700
- Is Kelly Frears around?
- She's copying her dissertation.

180
00:13:16,100 --> 00:13:17,900
[Laughs]

181
00:13:23,400 --> 00:13:25,600
- You're home.
- Home indeed.

182
00:13:25,800 --> 00:13:27,700
I love that you're home.

183
00:13:38,500 --> 00:13:40,400
[Laughs]

184
00:13:45,800 --> 00:13:50,700
<i>[TV, Female Newscaster]
Just days before Santa departs
on his annual gift-giving venture,</i>

185
00:13:51,000 --> 00:13:53,800
<i>he's been declared
physically fit to fly.</i>

186
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:57,600
<i>Santa got checked out by doctors at
the V.A. Hospital in Augusta, Georgia.</i>

187
00:13:57,900 --> 00:14:00,600
<i>After they declared
the jolly old elf in tiptop shape,</i>

188
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:04,200
Santa Claus took off into the wild
blue yonder for an early start.

189
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:06,800
In Sarajevo,
he spent the day with children,

190
00:14:07,100 --> 00:14:09,800
<i>handing out presents and
even helping them decorate...</i>

191
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:11,800
<i>the special Christmas tree.</i>

192
00:14:13,200 --> 00:14:15,800
<i>[Bell Clanging]</i>

193
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:18,200
<i>Santa and a sea of elves
took over the floor...</i>

194
00:14:18,400 --> 00:14:20,300
<i>at the Hong Kong
Futures Exchange.</i>

195
00:14:20,500 --> 00:14:22,700
<i>Market traders
bought Santa hats, donating...</i>

196
00:14:22,900 --> 00:14:24,800
<i>[TVShuts Off]</i>

197
00:14:45,400 --> 00:14:47,300
The turkey's a little dry,
isn't it?

198
00:14:47,500 --> 00:14:49,800
- [All] No.
- The turkey is perfect.

199
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:52,000
[Indistinct Chattering]

200
00:14:53,800 --> 00:14:56,900
- How many did you do last night?
- Last night? 2.9 million.

201
00:14:57,100 --> 00:15:00,500
Now you've got to be in the market
for more of these candied yams.

202
00:15:00,800 --> 00:15:02,200
Here you go.

203
00:15:02,300 --> 00:15:04,100
2.9 has got to be
the record.

204
00:15:04,300 --> 00:15:06,200
Look at those marshmallows.

205
00:15:06,400 --> 00:15:08,300
When I was there,
we did two million.

206
00:15:08,500 --> 00:15:10,800
- We thought that was a big deal.
- The glory days.

207
00:15:11,100 --> 00:15:13,500
- What'd they do the first night?
- The very first night?

208
00:15:13,700 --> 00:15:15,500
<i>- [Man #1] Twelve.
- [Man #2] Twelve thousand?</i>

209
00:15:15,700 --> 00:15:18,200
<i>- Hell, no. Twelve.
- [Chuck] That's right.</i>

210
00:15:18,400 --> 00:15:21,000
And they did the sort
right there on a card table.

211
00:15:21,200 --> 00:15:23,800
And Fred Smith had
that card table bronzed.

212
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:26,600
I've been hearing that
for five years.

213
00:15:26,800 --> 00:15:30,800
<i>- It's in his office today.
- They go from that to
the new hub up in Anchorage.</i>

214
00:15:31,100 --> 00:15:32,900
It's state of the art...
a perfect marriage...

215
00:15:33,100 --> 00:15:35,400
between technology
and systems management.

216
00:15:35,600 --> 00:15:38,300
Speaking of marriage, Chuck,
when are you gonna make
an honest woman out of Kelly?

217
00:15:38,500 --> 00:15:40,600
<i>[Excited Chattering]</i>

218
00:15:40,800 --> 00:15:43,500
- How long?
- Fourteen minutes into the meal.

219
00:15:43,700 --> 00:15:46,800
- You won. I owe you $5.
- So I win.

220
00:15:47,100 --> 00:15:49,000
- Way before the pie.
- I told him on the way up.

221
00:15:49,100 --> 00:15:52,100
Right about the time
the pie came out, the marriage...

222
00:15:52,400 --> 00:15:55,200
Kelly is still recovering from her
failed relationship with that parolee.

223
00:15:55,400 --> 00:15:57,500
He was a lawyer.

224
00:15:57,700 --> 00:15:59,900
I knew it had something to do
with raising your right hand...

225
00:16:00,100 --> 00:16:01,900
and swearing
to tell the truth.

226
00:16:02,100 --> 00:16:05,000
<i>Remember when he fell on the sidewalk
and broke his shoulder
at the wedding reception?</i>

227
00:16:05,200 --> 00:16:07,800
